(12, 2, '2018-04-13 00:00:00', '2018-04-13 00:00:00', '<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none\" style=\"padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 30px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-align: center;\"><a><img style=\"width: auto; max-width: 100%;\" src=\"http://thebrainstages.com/uploads/1/1/4/0/114011163/namesfor10b-screenshot2-enlarged_orig.jpg\" alt=\"Brain Stages Names for 10 Game\" /></a>\n<div style=\"display: block; font-size: 90%;\">Sofia plays the Names for 10 game with her fingers.</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-size: large;\">In the previous <a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/blog/names-for-ten-the-game-that-boosts-kids-math-skills\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Names for 10 post</a>, 7-year-old Eli showed you the secret for making math easier for kids (and adults) using a small (delicious) pile of M&amp;Ms.</span></div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: large;\"> 10 + 0,  9 + 1,  8 + 2,  7 + 3,  6 + 4,  5 + 5,\n4 + 6,  3 + 7,  2 + 8,  1 + 9,  0 + 10</span></strong></div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">Knowing those number partners, backwards and forwards — <strong>the commutative property (a + b = b + a)</strong> — makes so many other math concepts snap into place.\n\nAddition, subtraction, multiplication, division, trading and regrouping (we used to call it carrying and borrowing), fractions, decimals, percentages, time, and money — all become easier.\n\nIn the video below, Sofia shows you how to <strong>practice these critical number partners using her fingers.</strong>\n\nMost of us have 10 of those, right? No additional materials necessary.\n\nAnd playing Names for 10 is a great way to pass the time while you wait in line or ride in a car — with a big payoff!\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"wsite-youtube\" style=\"margin-bottom: 40px; margin-top: 10px;\">\n<div class=\"wsite-youtube-wrapper wsite-youtube-size-auto wsite-youtube-align-center\">\n<div class=\"wsite-youtube-container\"><iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/yxggj-iUpSM?wmode=opaque\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">Some kids (and their parents) <strong>do better remembering the names for 10 when they can see the numbers along with the groups of items.</strong>\n\nIn the next video, Jude, a second-grader, demonstrates how to play the game with <strong>number cards and pennies.</strong>\n\nEach time he moves an item from one pile to the other, he changes the cards to match the number of objects in each of the groupings that add up to 10.\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"wsite-youtube\" style=\"margin-bottom: 20px; margin-top: 10px;\">\n<div class=\"wsite-youtube-wrapper wsite-youtube-size-auto wsite-youtube-align-center\">\n<div class=\"wsite-youtube-container\"><iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/Y8aAiVfUIe8?wmode=opaque\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Notice that Jude wrote the numbers from 0 to 10 on colored paper, making sure the number partners were the same color.</strong>\n\nWhite paper is fine if that is what\'s available, but when number partners match in color, that gives kids one more way to cement the names for 10 in their brains.\n\n<strong>I’ve found that the more senses people use to learn things, the better they remember.</strong>\n\nMoving objects as well as number cards, especially color-coordinated ones, makes the groupings more visual. The physical shifting of objects also adds to kids’ familiarity with the number combinations that make 10.\n\nWhether your child is in first grade or fifth, or if YOU could use a math hack to make you better at quick calculations — at the grocery store, at work, or anywhere you’d like a fast answer — instantly knowing the names for 10 will make all the difference!\n\n<strong>If you have a math hack to share, please tell us about it in the comment section below.</strong>\n<strong>\nWe’d love to hear from you.</strong>\n\n<strong>And please share <a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/blog/names-for-ten-the-game-that-boosts-kids-math-skills\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Names for 10</a> with your friends!</strong>\n\n</div>\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">\n<div style=\"height: 0px; overflow: hidden;\"></div>\n<a class=\"wsite-button wsite-button-small wsite-button-normal\" href=\"/blog/names-for-ten-the-game-that-boosts-kids-math-skills\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span class=\"wsite-button-inner\">Check out the previous post: “Names for 10” Game</span></a>\n<div style=\"height: 30px; overflow: hidden;\"></div>\n</div>\n<div>\n<div id=\"389591743872304966\" class=\"wcustomhtml\" style=\"width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;\" align=\"left\"><!-- AddToAny BEGIN -->\n<div class=\"a2a_kit a2a_kit_size_32 a2a_default_style\"></div>\n<script async=\"\" src=\"https://static.addtoany.com/menu/page.js\"><br />\n</script> <!-- AddToAny END -->\n\n</div>\n</div>', 'More “Names for 10” Games to Boost Math Skills', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'more-ways-to-play-the-names-for-10-game-to-help-kids-become-math-wizards-and-you-too', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:48:36', '2018-10-10 19:48:36', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/2018/04/13/more-ways-to-play-the-names-for-10-game-to-help-kids-become-math-wizards-and-you-too/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(13, 2, '2018-05-18 00:00:00', '2018-05-18 00:00:00', '<div></div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">Summer vacation gives kids lots of opportunities for free play, which is great for mental processing and creativity. The break between grade levels is a perfect time for kids to get lots of exercise, take a breather from academics, and beef up imaginative play.\n\n<strong>That’s why summer reading is so great!</strong>\n\nBooks offer lots of springboard material to spark kids\' imaginations. Besides, going on mental adventures is a great way to pass the time during those lulls that happen on summer days or for winding down at the end of the bedtime ritual before lights out.\n\n<strong>The best part is children who read fun stories and play some of the Brain Stages games won\'t have to struggle to relearn stuff they\'ve forgotten over the break. In fact, their skills will be even sharper for the coming year.</strong>\n\nThe old saying \"practice makes perfect\" may be an overstatement, but most of us have found that we get better at things when we do them often. The scientific reason is repetition refines neural pathways in the brain and makes them more efficient. Conversely, neglecting those connections makes them rusty, and kids can get frustrated trying to get back into the swing of learning when school starts again.\n\nVisit the local library, book store, or both to find loads of fun for your kids (and you).\nIf your child is happy reading independently, awesome, but don\'t discount the together time in sharing stories, taking turns to read aloud. My kids and I used to check out both kinds of books on every trip to the library — one to read by ourselves and one to share.\n\nMy younger daughter and I read together through her high school years. We loved  discussing the characters, talking about the stories, and predicting what might happen next.\n\nI miss those days. A lot. Take the opportunity to read with your kids while you can.\n\n<strong>The trick is to get books your kids will LOVE, that will take them on adventures, make them laugh and fantasize about other places, sticky situations, and learn about problem solving.</strong>\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none\" style=\"padding-top: 10px; padding-bottom: 20px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-align: center;\"><a><img style=\"width: auto; max-width: 100%;\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/children-1822474-1920_orig.jpg\" alt=\"Brain Stages reading list\" /></a>\n<div style=\"display: block; font-size: 90%;\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">Fiction is about problem solving, and kids — well, all of us — can pick up a lot of ideas for real life reading imaginary stories. Authors go to great lengths to research settings, history, and customs to make their stories authentic (I know. I write young adult fiction).\n\nKids can learn as much from a novel, or more, than from a history or science book because they get exposed to concepts within the context of a story.\n\n<strong>For the next several weeks, I\'m going to post lists of tried-and-true titles that have a great reputation for enthralling scads of kids.</strong>\n\nSome of these books have been around for a while. Some are fairly new. All are awesome reads.\n\n<strong>Each list will be geared for a certain reading level.</strong>\n\n<strong>\n</strong><strong>Today\'s post is for second grade, give or take. And I listed series because good books are like cookies or chips — if your kids like one by a certain author, they\'ll probably want more.</strong>\n\nIf your children aren\'t up to this level yet, these will be wonderful read-aloud books to share. And if they usually read harder books, these titles can be quick and easy entertainment. After all, summer is a time to read for pleasure.\n\nI’ve included a list for girls and a list for boys since the genders often show different interests at this age. But feel free to expose both lists to your son or daughter. The best books are the ones they choose for themselves, and all of these books are fun.\n\n<strong>Please share these lists with your friends! Let\'s get lots of kids reading!</strong>\n\n<strong>      Eight Favorite Series of Second Grade Girls (and Boys Too)</strong>\n<ol>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Ivy+and+Bean+series+by+Annie+Barrows\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Ivy and Bean series by Annie Barrows</a>—two unlikely girls become friends and engage in hilarious antics together.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Mercy+Watson+to+the+Rescue+series+by+Kate+DiCamillo&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AMercy+Watson+to+the+Rescue+series+by+Kate+DiCamillo\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Mercy Watson to the Rescue series by Kate DiCamillo</a>—the Watsons’ pet pig gets into all kinds of ridiculous trouble trying to save the day.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Science+Series+by+April+Chloe+Terrazas&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AScience+Series+by+April+Chloe+Terrazas\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Super Smart Science Series for kids by April Chloe Terrazas</a>—complicated science concepts explained in an intriguing, understandable way for the younger set.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Gooney+Bird+Greene+series+by+Lois+Lowry&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AGooney+Bird+Greene+series+by+Lois+Lowry\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Gooney Bird Greene series by Lois Lowry</a>—second-grade girl tells “true stories” to her classmates that are quite outlandish and fun.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Toys+Go+Out%3A+Being+the+Adventures+of+a+Knowledgeable+Stingray%2C+a+Toughy+Little+Buffalo%2C+and+Someone+Called+Plastic+&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AToys+Go+Out%3A+Being+the+Adventures+of+a+Knowledgeable+Stingray%5Cc+a+Toughy+Little+Buffalo%5Cc+and+Someone+Called+Plastic+\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Toys Go Out: Being the Adventures of a Knowledgeable Stingray, a Toughy Little Buffalo, and Someone Called Plastic</em></a> by Emily Jenkins (trilogy)—little girls’ toys and their zany adventures together.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Junie+B.+Jones+series+by+Barbara+Park&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AJunie+B.+Jones+series+by+Barbara+Park\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Junie B. Jones series by Barbara Park</a>—hilarious, charming character kids love.</li>\n 	<li>Judy Moody series by Megan McDonald—feisty, socially awkward third-grader who usually learns lessons the hard way; great early chapter books with fun illustrations.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Amelia+Bedelia+chapter+book+series+by+Herman+Perish&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AAmelia+Bedelia+chapter+book+series+by+Herman+Perish\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Amelia Bedelia chapter book series by Herman Perish</a> (nephew of Peggy Perish, author of the picture book series)—entertaining stories that misinterpret idioms and homophones.</li>\n</ol>\n<strong>\nEight Favorite Series of Second Grade Boys (and Girls Too)</strong>\n<ol>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Touchdown+for+Tommy+by+Matt+Christopher&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ATouchdown+for+Tommy+by+Matt+Christopher\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Touchdown for Tommy</em> by Matt Christopher</a>—author of many books about sporty kids.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Stink+series+by+Megan+McDonald&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AStink+series+by+Megan+McDonald\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Stink series by Megan McDonald</a>—Judy Moody’s younger brother, a second-grade boy, gets into all kinds of fun predicaments with the best of intentions.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Stink-O-Pedia%3A+Super+Stink-y+Stuff+from+A+to+ZZZZ++Megan+McDonald&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AStink-O-Pedia%3A+Super+Stink-y+Stuff+from+A+to+ZZZZ++Megan+McDonald\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Stink-O-Pedia: Super Stink-y Stuff from A to ZZZZ</em></a>  also by Megan McDonald—a book of gross facts little boys love.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Super+Super+Smart+Science+Series+by+April+Chloe+Terrazas&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ASuper+Super+Smart+Science+Series+by+April+Chloe+Terrazas\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Super Smart Science series for kids by April Chloe Terrazas</a>—complicated science concepts explained in a way kids can understand and feel smart.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Nate+the+Great+series+by+Marjorie+Weinman+Sharmat&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ANate+the+Great+series+by+Marjorie+Weinman+Sharmat\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Nate the Great mystery series by Marjorie Weinman Sharmat</a>—for kids who need practice to get to grade-level reading and like a good whodunit.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Dog+Man+series+by+Dave+Pilkey&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ADog+Man+series+by+Dave+Pilkey\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Dog Man series by Dave Pilkey</a>—his latest silly series that has kids clamoring for more.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Magic+Tree+House+series+by+Mary+Pope+Osborne&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AMagic+Tree+House+series+by+Mary+Pope+Osborne\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Magic Tree House series by Mary Pope Osborne</a>—for various reading levels; brings history to life and promotes conversations about historical events.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Magic+School+Bus+series+by+Joanna+Cole&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AMagic+School+Bus+series+by+Joanna+Cole\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Magic School Bus series—mostly by Joanna Cole</a>, also various reading levels; entertaining read-along books about science concepts learned through adventure.</li>\n</ol>\n<span style=\"font-size: large;\"><strong>Remember to share this post with your friends. Let\'s get kids reading this summer!</strong></span>\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<div id=\"802094443335514253\" class=\"wcustomhtml\" style=\"width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;\" align=\"left\"><!-- AddToAny BEGIN -->\n<div class=\"a2a_kit a2a_kit_size_32 a2a_default_style\"></div>\n<script async=\"\" src=\"https://static.addtoany.com/menu/page.js\"><br />\n</script> <!-- AddToAny END -->\n\n</div>\n</div>', 'Summer Reading to Keep Kids Sharp: Grade 2', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'summer-fun-to-keep-kids-sharp-grade-2', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:50:03', '2018-10-10 19:50:03', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/2018/05/18/summer-fun-to-keep-kids-sharp-grade-2/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(14, 2, '2018-05-30 00:00:00', '2018-05-30 00:00:00', '<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none\" style=\"padding-top:0px;padding-bottom:30px;margin-left:0px;margin-right:0px;text-align:center\">\n<a><img src=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/children-studying-670663-1920_orig.jpg\" alt=\"Brain Stages Reading List\" style=\"width:auto;max-width:100%\"></a>\n<div style=\"display:block;font-size:90%\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align:left;\">\n<strong>Not only is low-stress reading during the summer a relaxing, healthy pastime that keeps skills sharp, but fun books can make a big difference in helping your child handle social situations.</strong>\n\nUsually, somewhere in third through fifth grade, children begin to recognize the need to navigate relationships. They wade through social dynamics with friends as well as other kids or adults they don’t get along with so well.\n\nBoth fiction and nonfiction stories present conflicts that eventually get solved. Kids can learn a lot about the ins and outs of how to deal with other people from characters in books. In other words:\n\n<strong>Watching how a problem gets worked out in a story is a safe way to process what to do in real-life circumstances</strong>.\n\nIf you read together sometimes, talk to your child about characters’ interactions and ask how they might handle a similar situation. Discussing harmless hypotheticals now could be a huge help in a future emotional scuffle.\n<strong>&nbsp;</strong>\n\n<font size=\"5\"><strong>Check out the list of 14 well-loved books below.</strong></font>\n\nAlthough the list is geared for fourth grade, younger children, or kids not quite ready&nbsp; to read at this level yet, will enjoy these as read-aloud books. Older kids or more advanced readers will sail through these fun stories, perfect for summer. Most of these titles can be found at your public library. The links go to Amazon pages in case you would like to find out more.\n<ol>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=The+Time+Warp+Trio\" target=\"_blank\">The Time Warp Trio</a>, swashbuckling series (16+ books) by Jon Scieszka—sends readers on a journey through events in history.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Magic+School+Bus&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AMagic+School+Bus\" target=\"_blank\">Magic School Bus</a> series (167+ picture and chapter books) most by Joanne Cole—for kids who like science, cool illustrations, and quirky characters. Animated versions reinforce comprehension—available for purchase or library checkout.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Hank+the+Cowdog+&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AHank+the+Cowdog+\" target=\"_blank\">Hank the Cowdog</a> series by John R. Erickson (68+ books)—a dog that always gets into trouble but saves the day in the end, a beloved ongoing series since 1982.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Charlotte%E2%80%99s+Web+and+Stuart+Little&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ACharlotte%E2%80%99s+Web+and+Stuart+Little\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Charlotte’s Web</em> and <em>Stuart Little</em></a> by E.B. White—long-time, beloved grade four stories.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss_2?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Roald&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ARoald\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Matilda, James and the Giant Peach, George’s Marvelous Machine, The BFG, The Witches,</em></a> and more by Roald Dahl—madcap clever books kids love.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss_2?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Heroes+of+Olympus&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AHeroes+of+Olympus\" target=\"_blank\">Heroes of Olympus</a> series (five books) by Rick Riordan—hugely popular with the action-loving set, leveled late third to early fifth grade for independent reading.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss_2?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=39+Clues&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3A39+Clues\" target=\"_blank\">39 Clues</a> series (eleven books) by various authors, including Rick Riordan—fantastic circumstances and nail-biting adventures kids can’t put down.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_ss_c_1_24?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=bruce+coville+magic+shop+books&amp;sprefix=bruce+coville+magic+shop%2Caps%2C5322&amp;crid=39VWLPOLFFHDI&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3Abruce+coville+magic+shop+books\" target=\"_blank\">Magic Shop</a> series (five books) by Bruce Coville—creepy, riveting stories (<em>The Monster’s Ring; Jeremy Thatcher, Dragon Hatcher; Jennifer Murdley’s Toad,</em> and <em>The Skull of Truth</em> are on fourth-grade reading level<em>; Juliet Dove, Queen of Love</em> is leveled for fifth grade).</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_ss_c_1_24?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Adventures+of+Captain+Underpants&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AAdventures+of+Captain+Underpants\" target=\"_blank\">Adventures of Captain Underpants</a> series (ten books) by Dav Pilkey—kooky stories with an unlikely hero who kids get a kick out of, and most of the series is written on fourth-grade reading level.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/gp/search/ref=sr_1_8_hso_sc_smartcategory_2?rh=n%3A4%2Ck%3ALittle+House+on+the+Prairie&amp;keywords=Little+House+on+the+Prairie&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1527708113&amp;sr=8-8-acs&amp;pf_rd_r=DV71KKTMR1VXJ65T4ESR&amp;pf_rd_t=301&amp;pd_rd_i=4&amp;pd_rd_r=b7499b9b-a315-40bb-bd5b-614ff0af3b5a&amp;pd_rd_w=boy8O&amp;pf_rd_p=3127749740981351126&amp;pf_rd_m=ATVPDKIKX0DER&amp;pd_rd_wg=lma06&amp;pf_rd_i=Little+House+on+the+Prairie&amp;pf_rd_s=desktop-sx-inline\" target=\"_blank\">Little House on the Prairie</a> series (nine books) by Laura Ingalls Wilder—historical fiction with lovable characters children have enjoyed for generations.</li>\n 	<li>\n<em><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Miraculous-Journey-Edward-Tulane-ebook/dp/B002NC733U/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1527708535&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=The+Miraculous+Journey+of+Edward+Tulane\" target=\"_blank\">The Miraculous Journey of Edward Tulane</a></em> by Kate DiCamillo—a toy rabbit gets lost and tossed into all kinds of crazy places and new adventures. DiCamillo has written several beloved stories at various reading levels.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Ddigital-text&amp;field-keywords=The+Spiderwick+Chronicles\" target=\"_blank\">The Spiderwick Chronicles</a> (four books) by Tony DiTerlizzi—three siblings discover a field guide in the attic, left by their ancestor, that leads them to a dangerous parallel world.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Ddigital-text&amp;field-keywords=Fudge+Judy+Bloom&amp;rh=n%3A133140011%2Ck%3AFudge+Judy+Bloom\" target=\"_blank\">Fudge</a> series (five books) by Judy Bloom—nine-year-old Peter is frustrated by high-maintenance, hilarious little brother Fudge.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Wrinkle-Time-Quintet-Books-1-5-ebook/dp/B00E71907M/ref=sr_1_5?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1527709744&amp;sr=1-5&amp;keywords=Wrinkle+in+Time\" target=\"_blank\">Wrinkle in Time</a> series (five books, four leveled fourth grade) by Madeleine L’ Engle—one of the first science-fiction fantasy series for children (1962), still beloved today.</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n<em>Note: For more lists of favorite titles categorized by reading level, check out these two websites: <a href=\"https://www.the-best-childrens-books.org/\" target=\"_blank\">The Best Children’s Books</a> and <a href=\"https://www.kidsbookseries.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Kids Book Series</a>.</em>\n\n<strong><font size=\"4\">Please share this post with friends and family. Let’s get kids reading this summer!</font></strong>\nIf you or your child have other favorite titles, please tell us about them in a comment below.\n\nAnd we\'d love for you to share reading experiences with your kids. How ’bout an idea for including relaxed reading in a busy family schedule?\n\nBest wishes for a lovely summer!\n\nTrish Wilkinson\n\nCo-author <em>Brain Stages: How to Raise Smart, Confident Kids and Have Fun Doing It, K – 5 (Available August 28, 2018, <a href=\"https://www.sandrajonaspublishing.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Sandra Jonas Publishing</a>)</em>\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<div id=\"443533773270165904\" align=\"left\" style=\"width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;\" class=\"wcustomhtml\">\n<!-- AddToAny BEGIN -->\n<div class=\"a2a_kit a2a_kit_size_32 a2a_default_style\">\n<a class=\"a2a_dd\" href=\"https://www.addtoany.com/share\"></a> <a class=\"a2a_button_facebook\"></a> <a class=\"a2a_button_twitter\"></a> <a class=\"a2a_button_google_plus\"></a> <a class=\"a2a_button_linkedin\"></a></div>\n<script async=\"\" src=\"https://static.addtoany.com/menu/page.js\"><br />\n</script> <!-- AddToAny END -->\n\n</div>\n</div>', 'Summer Reading to Keep Kids Sharp: Grade 4', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'summer-reading-to-keep-kids-sharp-grade-4', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:51:17', '2018-10-10 19:51:17', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/2018/05/30/summer-reading-to-keep-kids-sharp-grade-4/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(15, 2, '2018-06-21 00:00:00', '2018-06-21 00:00:00', '<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none\" style=\"padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 30px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-align: center;\">\n<div style=\"display: block; font-size: 90%;\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">Woo-hoo!\n\n<strong>November 12, 2018,</strong> <a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/book.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Brain Stages</em></a> will be ready for readers to snap it up and find out lots of insider info and fun, effective ways to nurture kids\' in line with how their brains develop.\n\nYou may have noticed <a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/book.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Brain Stages</em></a> has a new cover too. Double-whoo-hoo!\n\n<a href=\"https://www.sandrajonaspublishing.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Sandra, independent publisher extraordinaire</a>, revised the original cover with the feedback we received from friends and followers. Thanks so much to those of you who provided observations and suggestions!\n\n<a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/book.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Brain Stages</em></a> is a grade-by-grade book, a <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01DCHZE3A/ref=dp-kindle-redirect?_encoding=UTF8&amp;btkr=1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>What to Expect When You’re Expecting</em></a> for elementary school. The idea is to help create a solid academic, social, emotional, and physical foundation to raise happy, well-adjusted children.\n\n<a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/blog/too-much-coincidence-not-to-be-part-of-the-cosmic-plan\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">This project has been in the works for years.</a> But our sources are as up-to-date as you can get. Many cited articles and studies came out <em>this year</em>. I so appreciate Sandra and her crew for allowing me to update things all the way to the deadline to get <em>Brain Stages</em> to the printer for the release of the <a href=\"https://betweenthecoversblog.wordpress.com/2012/01/20/arcs-v-advance-review-copies/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">advance review copies</a> that will be out in mid-July.\n\nNew studies provide ever-greater detail to create an increasingly vivid picture for how children’s brains grow, develop, and learn.\n\nIn turn, I got to add valuable information, games, and activities up to the last second.\n\nSo. Much. Fun.\n\nNot that scientists have brains all figured out. I’m sure lots of new discoveries are on the horizon, and I’ll keep you in-the-know on the Brain Stages blog.\n\n(I’ve developed a sort of obsession with <a href=\"https://www.google.com/alerts\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Google Alerts</a>, to read articles and studies as soon as they’re published.)\n\nAnd Reading <a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/book.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Brain Stages</em></a> will make you feel like you’re talking with a trusted friend, a supportive one with answers backed up by the latest intel and thousands of hours of experience.\n\n<a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/book.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Brain Stages</em></a> has all kinds of features to save you (or someone you know) time, energy, and anguish to make the child-raising thing a whole lot of fun, such as:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Brain development and function and how to capitalize on meeting children wherever they are in their growth</li>\n 	<li>Social and emotional tendencies at each grade (individuals\' maturity may show up in more than one chapter as no two kids are alike)</li>\n 	<li>Academic expectations in each grade</li>\n 	<li>Ways to keep gifted kids engaged and develop their social skills</li>\n 	<li>How to handle special needs for happier, more successful children</li>\n 	<li>Games that boost mental and physical coordination to enhance creativity, math, language, and thinking abilities — best of all,  <em>they make family life more enjoyable and bring relationships closer</em></li>\n 	<li>Activities to foster communication skills</li>\n 	<li>Leveled book lists</li>\n 	<li>Tips for quick, healthy nutrition</li>\n 	<li>True stories that are sure to make you laugh, cry, or just give you relief to know you\'re not the only one . . .</li>\n</ul>\nI could go on and on. There\'s so much great stuff!\n\nBut don\'t worry, <em><a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/book.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Brain Stages</a></em> is broken into grade-level chapters, kindergarten through fifth, and will have an index to look up things that interest you.\n\nMan, I would\'ve LOVED to have had <em><a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/book.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Brain Stages</a></em> to support my child-raising journey in those early school years.\n\nWe’re living in exciting times!\n\nKids, parents, teachers, and caregivers have all been stressed out trying to keep up with societal expectations.\n\n<span style=\"font-size: large;\"><em>But less stress, more fun, and better results are right around the corner.</em></span>\n\nHere’s to happier, healthier kids, families, and schools everywhere!\n\n<strong>Please forward this email to your friends, and share the good news on Facebook and Twitter.</strong> Let’s give people something positive to anticipate and celebrate!\n\nLeave a comment if you have something you want to ask or tell us.\n(Maybe tell us what you think of the new cover?)\n\nBest wishes and happy summer!\n\nTrish Wilkinson, co-author\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<div id=\"473363422707327319\" class=\"wcustomhtml\" style=\"width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;\" align=\"left\"><!-- AddToAny BEGIN -->\n<div class=\"a2a_kit a2a_kit_size_32 a2a_default_style\"></div>\n<script async=\"\" src=\"https://static.addtoany.com/menu/page.js\"><br />\n</script> <!-- AddToAny END -->\n\n</div>\n</div>', '“Brain Stages” Release is November 12!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'brain-stages-how-to-raise-smart-confident-kids-and-have-fun-doing-it-k-5-will-be-released-august-28', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:50:59', '2018-10-10 19:50:59', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/2018/06/21/brain-stages-how-to-raise-smart-confident-kids-and-have-fun-doing-it-k-5-will-be-released-august-28/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(16, 2, '2018-07-06 00:00:00', '2018-07-06 00:00:00', '<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none \" style=\"padding-top: 10px; padding-bottom: 10px; margin-left: 0; margin-right: 0; text-align: center;\">\n\nSome kids love to pour over every printed word they can get their hands on. One of my daughters used to read cereal boxes and the backs of shampoo bottles. My nephew, however, would rather have gone to the dentist than pick up a book. His activity of choice was to play computer games, and my sister had to be diligent to keep his screen time moderate.\n\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\">\n\nWhat can you do if you have a child who doesn’t like to read? You know his neural pathways are busily forming and connecting. Reading practice is important. So how do you get him interested?\n\nThe two things that have worked best to get kids reading in my experience are:\n<ol>\n 	<li>Make them laugh, and</li>\n 	<li>Intrigue them</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none \" style=\"padding-top: 10px; padding-bottom: 10px; margin-left: 0; margin-right: 0; text-align: center;\"><a> <img style=\"width: 347; max-width: 100%;\" src=\"http://thebrainstages.com/uploads/1/1/4/0/114011163/published/boys-286151-640.jpg?1530924994\" alt=\"Picture\" /> </a>\n<div style=\"display: block; font-size: 90%;\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\">For example, most four- to seven-year-olds love to giggle at funny friends like <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Frog-Toad-Storybook-Treasury-Complete/dp/0062292587/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1530923960&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=frog+and+Toad\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Arnold Lobel’s Frog and Toad </a>or <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/?ie=UTF8&amp;keywords=henry+and+mudge&amp;tag=mh0b-20&amp;index=aps&amp;hvadid=78202830882208&amp;hvqmt=p&amp;hvbmt=bp&amp;hvdev=c&amp;ref=pd_sl_40y6afr91g_p\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Cynthia Rylant’s Henry and Mudge</a>. And these stories will give you the opportunity to talk about friendship and other values.\n\nFor tough nuts to crack when it comes to reading, <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Barbara+Park%E2%80%99s+Junie+B.+Jones+&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ABarbara+Park%E2%80%99s+Junie+B.+Jones+\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Barbara Park’s Junie B. Jones </a>books are a riot. Kids often can’t wait to read the next one—and the next. Fair warning, Junie isn’t a perfect character—which is largely what draws children to her adventures. Junie uses the word “stupid” a lot, she tends to be naughty, and her grammar is silly and improper. Though kids find these things hilarious, some parents find them inappropriate.\n\nPersonally, I appreciate how children distinguish between proper and improper behavior—how they tell me what Junie should have done instead of what she chose to do in the story. I also get a kick out of how they laugh when Junie says things like “thinked” instead of “thought.”\n\nBut if you’re uncomfortable with such a character, choose other books and series from the list below.\n\nFor instance, <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss_2?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=David+Adler+Cam+Jansen+&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ADavid+Adler+Cam+Jansen+\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">David Adler’s Cam Jansen </a>enthralls kids with how she finds and interprets clues, and solves mysteries in her neighborhood. Before you know it, your child will begin to put together clues with Cam and try to figure out the puzzle before she does.\n\nYou can begin reading the books on the list below aloud together. Then take turns reading paragraphs. As your child gets more confident and competent, you can switch off reading pages. After a while, he’ll probably take off on his own reading some of these books in the list below.\n\n<strong>11</strong> <strong>Series and Stories to Motivate Young Readers</strong>\n<ol>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Frog-Toad-Collection-Read-Book/dp/B015IZL1CC/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1530829227&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=frog+and+toad+series+books\">Frog and Toad series</a> by Arnold Lobel (4 books)—each has five simple, funny, sometimes instructive and touching stories about a frog and his friend, a toad.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_ss_c_1_23?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=henry+and+mudge+series&amp;sprefix=Henry+and+Mudge+series+%2Caps%2C267&amp;crid=PDZZCS8QYMQY&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3Ahenry+and+mudge+series\">Henry and Mudge series</a> by Cynthia Rylant (29 books, last count)—stories of Henry, a young boy, and his experiences with his huge dog, Mudge.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=You+Read+to+Me%2C+I%E2%80%99ll+Read+to+You+series++&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AYou+Read+to+Me%5Cc+I%E2%80%99ll+Read+to+You+series++\">You Read to Me, I’ll Read to You series</a> by Mary Ann Hoberman (5 books)—collections of simple short fairy tales, fables, scary stories, and more.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Young+Cam+Jansen+series+\">Young Cam Jansen series</a> by David Adler (20 books)—young-reader mysteries solved by a child detective who has a photographic memory.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/gp/bookseries/B00CKCWQ3A/ref=sr_bookseries_null_B00CKCWQ3A\">Tacky the Penguin</a> series by Helen Lester (7 books)—a funny, unique penguin learns to how to live in his community and celebrate his differences.</li>\n 	<li><em><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Wish-That-Duck-Beginner-Books/dp/0394800400/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1530827623&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=I+wish+I+had+Duck+Feet\">I wish I had Duck Feet</a></em> by Theo. LeSeig (a.k.a. Dr. Seuss), and lots of other Dr. Seuss books. Kids love LeSieg/Seuss’s strange characters and silly rhymes.</li>\n 	<li><em><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Emilys-First-100-Days-School/dp/0786813547/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1530827541&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=Emily%E2%80%99s+First+100+Days+of+School\">Emily’s First 100 Days of School</a></em> by Rosemary Wells—fun, adventure, math, what’s not to like in Emily’s, the resident bunny’s early school days?</li>\n 	<li><em><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Boy-Who-Loved-Words-ebook/dp/B00DACZ9PQ/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1530827454&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=the+boy+who+loved+words\">The Boy Who Loved Words</a></em> by Roni Schotter—a boy plays with words in silly, enjoyable ways that introduce vocabulary and word patterns.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Miss-Smiths-Incredible-Story-Book/dp/0525471332\">Miss Smith’s Incredible Story Book series</a> (4 books) by Michael Garland—teacher has a magic storybook where characters jump out and students go on adventures.</li>\n 	<li><em><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/There-Was-Old-Lady-Swallowed/dp/0670869392/ref=pd_lpo_sbs_14_img_1?_encoding=UTF8&amp;psc=1&amp;refRID=3DK86PFWAP8CMTJK32K7\">There Was an Old Lady Who Swallowed a Fly</a></em> by Ted Arnold—a funny story that builds on itself with a twist that first-graders love, in context that kids can decode.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Junie-First-Ever-Ebook-Collection-ebook/dp/B0082XLMQS/ref=cm_cr_arp_d_product_sims?ie=UTF8\">Junie B. Jones series by Barbara Park</a>, 17 madcap books of Junie’s adventures in kindergarten and 11 books about Junie in first grade</li>\n</ol>\nPsst. Third- and fourth-graders like these stories too, especially kids who need a little extra practice to improve their reading skills.\n\n<strong>Please pass along this post and share it on your social media so we can get as many kids reading as possible!</strong>\n\nDo you have other tried-and-true titles that have helped your child get into reading?\nPlease share them in a comment.\n\nHappy reading!\n\n<strong>Trish Wilkinson</strong>\n\n</div>', 'Entice Kids to Read with Giggles and Intrigue, K – 2', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'entice-kids-to-read-with-giggles-and-intrigue-k-2', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:52:20', '2018-10-10 19:52:20', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/2018/07/06/entice-kids-to-read-with-giggles-and-intrigue-k-2/', 0, 'post', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `tbstw_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(17, 2, '2018-08-08 00:00:00', '2018-08-08 00:00:00', '<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none \" style=\"padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 30px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-align: center;\">\n<div style=\"display: block; font-size: 90%; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"text-align: left; font-size: 16px;\">Do you have or know a child who writes letters backwards sometimes? The most commonly flipped letters are </span><strong style=\"text-align: left; font-size: 16px;\"><em>b</em></strong><span style=\"text-align: left; font-size: 16px;\"> and </span><strong style=\"text-align: left; font-size: 16px;\"><em>d,</em></strong><span style=\"text-align: left; font-size: 16px;\"> but kids have been known to form letters every which way.</span></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\n\nWhen I was little, I often confused the b and d until I learned the trick Eli and I are about to show you in the less than 3-minute video. The <strong>Red Light, Green Light</strong> game, given to me by a resource specialist in San Diego, incorporates the trick my second-grade teacher gave me (more decades ago than I\'d like to admit).\n\n<strong>Playing Red Light, Green Light has helped kids of all ages, even children who have learning disabilities, figure out which way the letters are supposed to go — not just the b and d but the whole alphabet. </strong>\n\nWe take writing skills for granted, <a href=\"http://theconversation.com/explainer-how-the-brain-changes-when-we-learn-to-read-76783\">but several kinds of connections between neurons, synapses, and little organs in the brain are involved in processing language</a>. It isn’t a wonder that kids get mixed up sometimes. Holding the pencil with an extra finger on top or some other impractical position can make writing harder (click <a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/blog/the-best-pencil-grip-the-secret-to-easier-writing\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">here</a> to see how to fix pencil grip). Add starting letters in wonky places, or writing letters from the bottom-up instead of the top-down, and writing can become an unpleasant chore.\n\nLuckily, with a bit of fun and practice, neural pathways can access revised information stored in brain’s memory centers.\n\nThe<strong> Red Light, Green Light </strong>game retrains kids how to write letters from <strong>top to bottom</strong> and practices movement from <strong>left to right</strong>, which can improve both reading and writing.\n\nWatch Eli play the game with me in the short video. Initially, when we played the game a few weeks ago, he wrote both <strong><em>b</em></strong> and <em><strong>d</strong></em> from bottom to top. Now that he knows how to form the letters from top to bottom, he told me (and Michelle, his mom, confirmed) that writing has gotten much easier for him. And his reading has improved too!\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"wsite-video\">\n<div class=\"wsite-video-wrapper wsite-video-height-480 wsite-video-align-center\" title=\"Video: red_light_green_light_game_700.mp4\">\n<div id=\"wsite-video-container-884805677828382045\" class=\"wsite-video-container\" style=\"margin: 10px 0 10px 0;\"><iframe id=\"video-iframe-884805677828382045\" src=\"about:blank\" frameborder=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"> 						</iframe> <script> 							document.getElementById(\"video-iframe-884805677828382045\").style.opacity = 0; 							document.getElementById(\"wsite-video-container-884805677828382045\").style.background = \"none\"; 							var videoIframe884805677828382045Content = \'<!DOC\'+\'TYPE ht\'+\'ml>\' 								+ \'<he\'+\'ad>\' 								+ \'<scr\'+\'ipt type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/2.1.4/jquery.min.js\">\\x3C/script>\' 								+ \'<scr\'+\'ipt type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"//www.weebly.com/weebly/apps/generateVideo.php?source=weebly&output=js&elementid=884805677828382045&user=114011163&ineditor=0&align=center&margintop=10px&marginbottom=10px&downloadable=1&height=480&video=red_light_green_light_game_700.mp4&image=red_light_green_light_game_700.jpg\">\\x3C/script>\' 								+ \'\'+\'ad>\' 								+ \'<bo\'+\'dy style=\"margin:0; padding: 0;border:none;overflow:hidden;\">\' 								+ \'\'+\'dy>\'+\'ml>\'; 							setTimeout(function() { 								var videoIframe884805677828382045Actual =  document.getElementById(\"video-iframe-884805677828382045\").contentDocument; 								videoIframe884805677828382045Actual.open().write(videoIframe884805677828382045Content); 								videoIframe884805677828382045Actual.close(); 							}, 500); 						</script>\n\n<style> 							#wsite-video-container-884805677828382045{ 								background: url(//www.weebly.com/uploads/red_light_green_light_game_700.jpg); 							}  							#video-iframe-884805677828382045{ 								background: url(//cdn2.editmysite.com/images/util/videojs/play-icon.png?1534365523); 							}  							#wsite-video-container-884805677828382045, #video-iframe-884805677828382045{ 								background-repeat: no-repeat; 								background-position:center; 							}  							@media only screen and (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2), 								only screen and (        min-device-pixel-ratio: 2), 								only screen and (                min-resolution: 192dpi), 								only screen and (                min-resolution: 2dppx) { 									#video-iframe-884805677828382045{ 										background: url(//cdn2.editmysite.com/images/util/videojs/@2x/play-icon.png?1534365523); 										background-repeat: no-repeat; 										background-position:center; 										background-size: 70px 70px; 									} 							} 						</style></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Here\'s how to play Red Light-Green Light</strong>:\n\n1. You’ll need a red crayon and a green crayon. Why crayons? Because kids can feel the wax, and the tactile sensation helps to solidify the concept. You’ll also need lined paper. Any kind will do, but in most grocery stores now, they sell tablets with a top line, a middle dotted line, or \"belt line\", and a bottom line. When learning, or relearning, how to form letters, that belt line is helpful.\n\n2. Remind your child that green means “GO” and red means “STOP.” Put a green dot where the letter begins and continue with green dots for the entire letter on the first several tries. Place a red dot to signify where the letter should stop. Watch to make sure your child begins and ends the letter in the right places.\n\n</div>\n<span style=\"display: table; width: auto; position: relative; float: left; max-width: 100%; ;clear: left; margin-top: 0px; *margin-top: 0px;\"><a><img class=\"galleryImageBorder wsite-image\" style=\"border-width: 0; max-width: 100%; margin: 0px 20px 30px 0px;\" src=\"http://thebrainstages.com/uploads/1/1/4/0/114011163/editor/img-1869.jpg?1525727356\" alt=\"Brain Stages Writing Hack\" /></a></span>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left; display: block;\"><em>Note: </em>A lowercase <strong><em>b</em> </strong>starts at the top line, goes down to the bottom line, up to the middle, and around to form the “belly.” After your child gets familiar with how to form the letter, give the direction “Down, up, and around,” and have your child say it with you.</div>\n\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; clear: both; visibility: hidden;\" />\n\n<span style=\"display: table; width: auto; position: relative; float: left; max-width: 100%; ;clear: left; margin-top: 0px; *margin-top: 0px;\"><a><img class=\"galleryImageBorder wsite-image\" style=\"border-width: 0; max-width: 100%; margin: 0px 20px 20px 0px;\" src=\"http://thebrainstages.com/uploads/1/1/4/0/114011163/editor/img-1872.jpg?1525727322\" alt=\"Brain Stages Writing Hack\" /></a></span>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left; display: block;\">A lowercase <strong><em>d</em> </strong>is formed like an <em><strong>a</strong></em> with a long stick. Like an <em><strong>a</strong></em> begins just below the middle line, goes up to the middle line, and around to form the “derrier” (French for backside — kids get a kick out of that). The <em><strong>d</strong></em> is formed like an <strong><em>a</em></strong>, except the pencil reaches all the way to the top line and back down to the bottom line. Say with your child, “Around, up, and down.\"</div>\n\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; clear: both; visibility: hidden;\" />\n\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">3. When your child feels comfortable with tracing the letters with lots of green dots, make more letters with fewer and fewer dots until no more are needed. Place only a green dot to mark where the letter begins and a red dot where the letter is to end.\n\n<em>Hint: </em>Get a crayon sharpener (pencil sharpeners work too). Making dots with dull crayons makes them bigger than optimal.\n\nIf your child still reverses a letter using green and red “lights,” help create a tactile memory by writing the entire letter with a green crayon<em>.</em> Then gently guide the pencil in his hand to trace the letter 10 times as consistently as possible.\n\nAnd have fun!\n\nBe liberal with the car engine sounds when you start at the green light and the brake sounds when you stop at the red light.\n\nPlay <strong>Red Light, Green Light </strong>for several days in a row and watch your child\'s writing transform!\n\nThe beauty of educational games is they often have wonderful side effects. <strong>Red Light, Green Light</strong> helps in grasping direction of movement. Truly understanding left to right is a huge help in learning to read.\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<div id=\"736789382366100066\" class=\"wcustomhtml\" style=\"width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;\" align=\"left\"><!-- AddToAny BEGIN -->\n<div class=\"a2a_kit a2a_kit_size_32 a2a_default_style\">\n\n\n\n</div>\n<script async=\"\" src=\"https://static.addtoany.com/menu/page.js\"></script>\n<!-- AddToAny END -->\n\n</div>\n</div>', '“Red Light–Green Light”: Make Kids Better Writers', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'red-light-green-light-make-kids-better-readers', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:38:59', '2018-10-10 19:38:59', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/2018/08/08/red-light-green-light-make-kids-better-readers/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(18, 2, '2018-08-17 00:00:00', '2018-08-17 00:00:00', '<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none\" style=\"padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 10px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-align: center;\">\n<div style=\"display: block; font-size: 90%; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"text-align: left; font-size: 16px;\">If you think people are either born good at numbers—or they aren’t—you might be excited to know that a little practice with a few simple games can get anyone calculating quickly in their heads.</span></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\n\nMy older sisters and younger brother always loved math, but I never liked numbers much growing up. My siblings, even my cousins, are all accountants and engineers. The rest of my family seemed to like numbers for numbers’ sake.\n\nMe? I always liked the creative stuff—teaching, storytelling, singing, writing novels and articles, and now <em>Brain Stages</em> with Jackie to help people raise smart, happy kids.\n\nWith math, I went through the motions—I did what I was told to solve problems, usually got the right answer, but didn’t understand how I got there.\n\nAnd forget figuring the cost of something at the grocery store in my head, or any other real-life reason for using math. Without paper and pencil or a calculator, I was lost.\n\nThen I started teaching kids — and I wanted them to understand math better than I did. A fellow teacher showed me the <a href=\"/blog/names-for-ten-the-game-that-boosts-kids-math-skills\">Names for 10 game</a>, and I learned the same number patterns repeated over and over.\n\n<strong>I learned to apply patterns to larger numbers as well as decimals—in my head!</strong>\n\nBefore I knew it, with friends, I’d pop out how much a collection of things we’d need for a party would cost. I’d add sales tax (I lived in California then, where they have sales tax—go, Oregon, where we don’t!), and come up with the amount each person would need to contribute.\n\nPeople used to widen their eyes at me and pull out their calculators. I have to admit that my smile got a little smug sometimes.\n\n<strong>Did I somehow get smarter? Heck, no. Ha!</strong>\n\nIn playing the <a href=\"/blog/more-ways-to-play-the-names-for-10-game-to-help-kids-become-math-wizards-and-you-too\">Names for 10 game</a> with kids and showing them how to count coins like in the video below, where Eli counts coins and puts together different combinations to make the same amounts, <strong>I developed and reconfigured neural pathways in my brain.</strong>\n\nAnd so can you!\n\nYour kids can too!\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<div id=\"958802795733885836\" class=\"wcustomhtml\" style=\"width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;\" align=\"left\"><iframe src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/284257095\" width=\"640\" height=\"352\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe>\n\n<a href=\"https://vimeo.com/284257095\">Coin Video</a> from <a href=\"https://vimeo.com/user83464375\">Kirdy Molan</a> on <a href=\"https://vimeo.com\">Vimeo</a>.\n\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\">\nOnce these patterns become second nature, you won’t believe how many other math concepts and operations will become easier.\n\nIf you missed the two Names for 10 posts, you can find them <a href=\"/blog/names-for-ten-the-game-that-boosts-kids-math-skills\">here</a> and <a href=\"/blog/more-ways-to-play-the-names-for-10-game-to-help-kids-become-math-wizards-and-you-too\">here</a>.\n\n<strong>How do your kids earn money to toss in a piggy bank and count it later?</strong>\n\nIf you know another helpful math game, please share it with us!\n\nHappy counting!\n\nTrish W.\n\n</div>', 'Help Your Child Become a Math Whiz—And Become One Too!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'help-your-child-become-a-math-whiz-and-become-one-too', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:39:44', '2018-10-10 19:39:44', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/2018/08/17/help-your-child-become-a-math-whiz-and-become-one-too/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(19, 2, '2018-10-04 23:01:39', '2018-10-04 23:01:39', '<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Learn More About Brain Stages</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"left\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"alignleft\"><img src=\"http://thebrainstages.com/uploads/1/1/4/0/114011163/published/twilkinson-tealblouse.jpg?1518317464\" alt=\"Picture\"/><figcaption>Trish Wilkinson, Author and Licensed Educator<br/></figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\nHi there,\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Do you have a question? Would you like to submit a video with your child that you think would be helpful for other parents and their kids? Would you like me to speak or do a workshop in your community?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whatever is on your mind, I\'d love to hear from you! </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Trish Wilkinson<br/>Co-author<br/><em>Brain Stages — </em><em>How to Raise Smart, Confident Kids and Have Fun Doing It,<br/>K – 5</em><br/>Available August 28, 2018, <a href=\"https://www.sandrajonaspublishing.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Sandra Jonas Publishing</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:wpforms/form-selector {\"formId\":\"137\"} /-->', 'Contact Trish', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'contact-trish-brain-stages', '', '', '2018-10-10 20:53:33', '2018-10-10 20:53:33', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/contact-trish-brain-stages/', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(20, 2, '2018-10-04 23:01:39', '2018-10-04 23:01:39', '<h2 class=\"wsite-content-title\"><span style=\"color: #515151; font-size: medium;\"><em><strong>How to Raise Smart, Confident Kids and Have Fun Doing It, K–5</strong></em></span></h2>\n<div>\n<div style=\"height: 20px; overflow: hidden; width: 100%;\">&nbsp;</div>\n</div>\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":33,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/brainstagescover-exp4-7d-stroke_1_orig.jpg\" alt=\"Brain Stages Cover\" class=\"wp-image-33\"/><figcaption>Brain Stages Cover</figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Who says kids don’t come with instructions?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We’re pleased to announce the first edition of <em>Brain Stages</em>, a comprehensive grade-by-grade guide through the elementary school years.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>​Written in a friendly, conversational style, this book gives you useful tools to boost your kids’ brainpower and help them develop social skills, laying the foundation for them to become happy, successful adults.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Backed by research and experience and filled with fun games, insider information, and amazing life hacks for raising kids, <em>Brain Stages</em> invites parents and caregivers to enjoy kids more and stress less while bringing up well-adjusted humans.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<br>\n<br>\n<p style=\"color: #331D6E\"><em><strong>“Finally, a guide to help your child enjoy learning based upon the latest brain research and explained by a veteran teacher, who offers parents fun, practical strategies.”<br>— S. Cradduck, Licensed Educational Psychologist​.</strong></em></p>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Brain Stages Book', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'brain-stages-book-brain-stages', '', '', '2018-10-13 22:10:35', '2018-10-13 22:10:35', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/brain-stages-book-brain-stages/', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(21, 2, '2018-10-04 23:01:39', '2018-10-04 23:01:39', '&nbsp;\r\n<div class=\"wsite-section-wrap\">\r\n<div class=\"wsite-section wsite-body-section wsite-background-5\">\r\n<div class=\"wsite-section-content\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"wsite-section-elements\">\r\n<div>\r\n<div class=\"wsite-multicol\">\r\n<div class=\"wsite-multicol-table-wrap\" style=\"margin: 0 -15px;\">\r\n<table class=\"wsite-multicol-table\">\r\n<tbody class=\"wsite-multicol-tbody\">\r\n<tr class=\"wsite-multicol-tr\">\r\n<td class=\"wsite-multicol-col\" style=\"width: 33.333333333333%; padding: 0 15px;\">\r\n<div>\r\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none \" style=\"padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 10px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-align: center;\"><a href=\"/blog/a-salty-kick-start-for-reading-and-writing\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">\r\n<img style=\"width: auto; max-width: 100%;\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/saltykickstart-cropped_orig.jpg\" alt=\"Brain Stages Writing Skills\" />\r\n</a>\r\n<div style=\"display: block; font-size: 90%;\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h2 class=\"wsite-content-title\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: x-large;\"><a href=\"/blog/a-salty-kick-start-for-reading-and-writing\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">A Salty Kick Start for Reading and Writing</a></span></h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td class=\"wsite-multicol-col\" style=\"width: 33.333333333333%; padding: 0 15px;\">\r\n<div>\r\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none \" style=\"padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 10px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-align: left;\"><a href=\"/blog/the-best-pencil-grip-the-secret-to-easier-writing\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">\r\n<img style=\"width: auto; max-width: 100%;\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/pencilgrip-screenshot3-cropped_orig.jpg\" alt=\"Brain Stages Pencil Grip\" />\r\n</a>\r\n<div style=\"display: block; font-size: 90%;\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h2 class=\"wsite-content-title\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"/blog/the-best-pencil-grip-the-secret-to-easier-writing\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-size: x-large;\">The Best Pencil Grip: The Secret to Easier Writing</span></a></h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td class=\"wsite-multicol-col\" style=\"width: 33.333333333333%; padding: 0 15px;\">\r\n<div>\r\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none \" style=\"padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 10px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-align: right;\"><a href=\"/blog/names-for-ten-the-game-that-boosts-kids-math-skills\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">\r\n<img style=\"width: auto; max-width: 100%;\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/namesfor10-screenshot1-homepage_orig.jpg\" alt=\"Brain Stages Math Game\" />\r\n</a>\r\n<div style=\"display: block; font-size: 90%;\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h2 class=\"wsite-content-title\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"/blog/names-for-ten-the-game-that-boosts-kids-math-skills\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-size: x-large;\">“Names for 10” Game to Boost Math Skills</span></a></h2>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"wsite-spacer\" style=\"height: 50px;\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>', 'Home', '', 'trash', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'brain-stages-brain-stages__trashed', '', '', '2018-10-04 23:33:02', '2018-10-04 23:33:02', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/brain-stages-brain-stages/', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(22, 2, '2018-10-04 23:01:39', '2018-10-04 23:01:39', '<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Raise Smart, Confident Kids and Have Fun Doing It!</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"//downloads.mailchimp.com/js/signup-forms/popup/unique-methods/embed.js\" data-dojo-config=\"usePlainJson: true, isDebug: false\"></script><script type=\"text/javascript\">window.dojoRequire([\"mojo/signup-forms/Loader\"], function(L) { L.start({\"baseUrl\":\"mc.us15.list-manage.com\",\"uuid\":\"343d8cd6e346b50a86cc67d1b\",\"lid\":\"6791140e42\",\"uniqueMethods\":true}) })</script></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Welcome to Brains Stages, where you can find out the latest research and practical tips for raising and educating children <em><strong>in harmony with how their brains develop</strong></em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":33,\"align\":\"center\",\"width\":402,\"height\":596} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter is-resized\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/brainstagescover-exp4-7d-stroke_1_orig.jpg\" alt=\"Brain Stages Cover\" class=\"wp-image-33\" width=\"402\" height=\"596\"/><figcaption>Brain Stages Cover</figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You\'ll find answers to questions in accordance with science such as:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>What can you do to give your child a leg up in today’s competitive society while raising a happy, well-adjusted future adult?</li><li>How can you get a disinterested kid engaged in school and learning? (<em>Hint:</em> It\'s probably not what you think.)</li><li>How can you help an anxious child relax for better learning?</li><li>What sure-fire ways can you help a struggling child get caught up in math or reading — and have FUN while you\'re at it?</li><li>How can you get your gifted child\'s needs met?</li><li>What can you do to help kids develop social skills — even if dealing with people isn\'t <em>your</em> best thing?</li><li>What’s the most effective way to empower children for a successful life? (<em>Hint</em>: This is also probably not what you think.) And much more!</li><li><strong>BONUS: You\'ll find your own skills improving and your views more empowering—right along with your kids!</strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/jackie_headshot-2.jpeg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"107\" data-link=\"http://localhost:8888/about-brain-stages-brain-stages/jackie_headshot-3/\" class=\"wp-image-107\"/><figcaption>Jackie Frischknecht, PhD</figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/trish_headshot-1.jpeg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"108\" data-link=\"http://localhost:8888/about-brain-stages-brain-stages/trish_headshot-2/\" class=\"wp-image-108\"/><figcaption>Trish Wilkinson, Author and Licensed Educator<br/></figcaption></figure></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jacqueline Frischknecht, PhD and mother of three, and I, Trish Wilkinson, mother of two and veteran teacher, are excited to share with you what we’ve learned through thousands of hours of experience and ongoing research. On the <a href=\"/blog.html\">Brain Stages blog</a>, you\'ll find out how brains work, practical ways to enjoy kids more and stress less, and how to optimize situations as well as solve problems.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Even Better, <strong><em>Bra</em><em>in Stages: How to Raise Smart, Confident Kids and Have Fun Doing It, K – 5</em></strong>, our grade-by-grade guide through the elementary school years, will be available November 13, 2018 to make your life with kids a lot easier and way more pleasant!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Please consider joining our community of people who want to make the world a better place for kids and parents by clicking the box at the bottom of this page to get exclusive tips.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To learn the surprising way Brain Stages came to be, click <a href=\"/blog/too-much-coincidence-not-to-be-part-of-the-cosmic-plan\">here.</a><br/>To find out more about the <em>Brain Stages</em> book, click <a href=\"/book.html\">here.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thanks for visiting!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>-Trish Wilkinson</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-0 is-cropped\"></ul>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->', 'About Brain Stages', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'about-brain-stages-brain-stages', '', '', '2018-10-13 22:53:28', '2018-10-13 22:53:28', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/about-brain-stages-brain-stages/', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(23, 2, '2018-10-04 23:01:39', '2018-10-04 23:01:39', '\n	<div class=\"wsite-section-wrap\">\n	<div class=\"wsite-section wsite-body-section wsite-background-21\">\n		<div class=\"wsite-section-content\">\n          <div class=\"container\">\n			<div class=\"wsite-section-elements\">\n				<div><div class=\"wsite-multicol\"><div class=\"wsite-multicol-table-wrap\" style=\"margin:0 -10px;\">\n	<table class=\"wsite-multicol-table\">\n		<tbody class=\"wsite-multicol-tbody\">\n			<tr class=\"wsite-multicol-tr\">\n				<td class=\"wsite-multicol-col\" style=\"width:67.699530516432%; padding:0 10px;\">\n					\n						\n\n<h2 class=\"wsite-content-title\">\n<font color=\"#248d6c\">Raise Smart, Confident Kids and Have Fun Doing It</font><br>\n</h2>\n\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align:left;\">New brain research comes out almost daily, providing insight as to how kids develop and learn. Brain Stages, in accordance with science, answers questions that so many parents struggle with, such as:<ul>\n<li>What can you do to give your child a leg up in today’s competitive society while raising a happy, well-adjusted future adult?</li>\n<li>How can you get your disinterested kid engaged in school and learning? (<em>Hint:</em> It\'s probably not what you think.)</li>\n<li>How can you help an anxious child relax for better learning?</li>\n<li>What sure-fire ways can you help a struggling child get caught up in math or reading—and have FUN together while you\'re doing it?</li>\n<li>How can you get your gifted kid\'s needs met to stimulate interest in classroom activities?</li>\n<li>How can you help your child develop social skills—even if dealing with people isn\'t <em>your</em> best thing?</li>\n<li>What’s the most effective way to empower your child for a successful life? (<em>Hint</em>: This is also probably not what you think.)</li>\n</ul>\n<br>Though we still have much to grasp about how kids learn, technology has shed considerable light on effective ways to stimulate children’s organic ability to absorb and apply experiences <font color=\"#060606\"><em><font color=\"#000\"><strong>in harmony with how their brains develop</strong></font></em>.</font><br><br>Jacqueline Frischknecht, PhD, and mother of three, and I, Trish Wilkinson, mother of two and veteran teacher, set out to share with you what we’ve learned through thousands of hours of experience and research.<br><br>We hope you enjoy the games, activities, how-tos, and insider information to support school-age kids’ brain development to help ensure their well-being and academic success. Our goal is for your family to have fun together at every age, while you raise smart, happy kids.<br> <br>Even better, you’ll have access to everything we’ve learned in the past 35 years in a much more comprehensive, entertaining, organized fashion this spring 2018, when <a href=\"https://www.sandrajonaspublishing.com/\">Sandra Jonas Publishing</a> releases our book:<br><br><em><strong>Brain Stages: How to Raise Smart, Happy Kids and Have Fun Doing It, K–5</strong></em><br><strong><em>                                        </em></strong><br>Sadly, Jackie passed away before we finished the book. It is my hope that she would be pleased with our <em>Brain Stages</em> website and publication.<br> <br>If you’d like to submit a video of your child doing an activity that you believe could help other parents and kids, or you have helpful information to share, please leave send an email to <a href=\"mailto:trish@thebrainstages.com\">trish@thebrainstages.com</a>.<br><br>We\'d also love for you to join our community of parents, grandparents, caregivers, educators, and other people who want to help make the world a better place by asking questions or writing helpful comments after blog posts.<br><br>Thanks for visiting!<br><br>Trish Wilkinson</div>\n\n<div style=\"text-align:left;\">\n<div style=\"height:0px;overflow:hidden\"></div>\n<span class=\"wsite-social wsite-social-default\"><a class=\"first-child wsite-social-item wsite-social-facebook\" href=\"https://www.facebook.com/trish.wilkinson.395?ref=bookmarks\" target=\"_blank\" alt-text=\"Facebook\"><span class=\"wsite-social-item-inner\"></span></a><a class=\"wsite-social-item wsite-social-twitter\" href=\"https://twitter.com/TrishWilkinson\" target=\"_blank\" alt-text=\"Twitter\"><span class=\"wsite-social-item-inner\"></span></a><a class=\"wsite-social-item wsite-social-linkedin\" href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/trish-wilkinson-4875646/\" target=\"_blank\" alt-text=\"Linkedin\"><span class=\"wsite-social-item-inner\"></span></a><a class=\"last-child wsite-social-item wsite-social-mail\" href=\"mailto:trish@thebrainstages.com\" target=\"_blank\" alt-text=\"Mail\"><span class=\"wsite-social-item-inner\"></span></a></span>\n<div style=\"height:0px;overflow:hidden\"></div>\n</div>\n\n\n					\n				</td>				<td class=\"wsite-multicol-col\" style=\"width:32.300469483568%; padding:0 10px;\">\n					\n						\n\n<div><div class=\"wsite-multicol\"><div class=\"wsite-multicol-table-wrap\" style=\"margin:0 -15px;\">\n	<table class=\"wsite-multicol-table\">\n		<tbody class=\"wsite-multicol-tbody\">\n			<tr class=\"wsite-multicol-tr\">\n				<td class=\"wsite-multicol-col\" style=\"width:27.920227920228%; padding:0 15px;\">\n					\n						\n\n<div class=\"wsite-spacer\" style=\"height:50px;\"></div>\n\n\n					\n				</td>				<td class=\"wsite-multicol-col\" style=\"width:72.079772079772%; padding:0 15px;\">\n					\n						\n\n<div style=\"text-align:left;\">\n<div style=\"height:0px;overflow:hidden\"></div>\n<span class=\"wsite-social wsite-social-default\"><a class=\"first-child wsite-social-item wsite-social-facebook\" href=\"https://www.facebook.com/trish.wilkinson.395?ref=bookmarks\" target=\"_blank\" alt-text=\"Facebook\"><span class=\"wsite-social-item-inner\"></span></a><a class=\"wsite-social-item wsite-social-twitter\" href=\"https://twitter.com/TrishWilkinson\" target=\"_blank\" alt-text=\"Twitter\"><span class=\"wsite-social-item-inner\"></span></a><a class=\"wsite-social-item wsite-social-linkedin\" href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/trish-wilkinson-4875646/\" target=\"_blank\" alt-text=\"Linkedin\"><span class=\"wsite-social-item-inner\"></span></a><a class=\"last-child wsite-social-item wsite-social-mail\" href=\"mailto:trish@thebrainstages.com\" target=\"_blank\" alt-text=\"Mail\"><span class=\"wsite-social-item-inner\"></span></a></span>\n<div style=\"height:20px;overflow:hidden\"></div>\n</div>\n\n\n					\n				</td>			</tr>\n		</tbody>\n	</table>\n</div></div></div>\n\n<div><div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none \" style=\"padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0px;margin-right:0px;text-align:center\">\n<a>\n<img src=\"http://thebrainstages.com/uploads/1/1/4/0/114011163/published/889a46af6e2c44cd91145936ae365313_1.jpg\" alt=\"Picture\" style=\"width:194;max-width:100%\">\n</a>\n<div style=\"display:block;font-size:90%\">Trish Wilkinson</div>\n</div></div>\n\n<div><div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none \" style=\"padding-top:30px;padding-bottom:30px;margin-left:0px;margin-right:0px;text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/jackief-img-0844-color_1.jpg\" rel=\"lightbox\" onclick=\"if (!lightboxLoaded) return false\">\n<img src=\"http://thebrainstages.com/uploads/1/1/4/0/114011163/editor/jackief-img-0844-color_1.jpg\" alt=\"Picture\" style=\"width:195;max-width:100%\">\n</a>\n<div style=\"display:block;font-size:90%\">Jackie Frischknecht</div>\n</div></div>\n\n<div><div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none \" style=\"padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center\">\n<a>\n<img src=\"http://thebrainstages.com/uploads/1/1/4/0/114011163/published/brainstagescover-comp11-newkids-6x9-stroke.jpg?1520050184\" alt=\"Picture\" style=\"width:226;max-width:100%\">\n</a>\n<div style=\"display:block;font-size:90%\"></div>\n</div></div>\n\n\n					\n				</td>			</tr>\n		</tbody>\n	<