(90, 1, '2018-10-10 19:49:05', '2018-10-10 19:49:05', '<div></div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">Whether your child is a math wiz or struggling to understand and apply new concepts, learning all the number combinations that add up to 10 can be THE thing to set your child on a trajectory for major success in math.\n\nWhy? Because we live in a society of base 10. Weights and measures, money, fractions, decimals, percentages, just about everything can be related to our base 10 system.\n\n<strong>The super math hack for kids is to learn all the “names for 10” by heart.</strong>\n<strong>     10 + 0,</strong> <strong>  9 + 1,</strong>  8 + 2,<strong>  7 + 3,</strong>  6 + 4,<strong>  5 + 5,</strong>  4 + 6,<strong>  3 + 7,</strong>  2 + 8,<strong>  1 + 9,</strong>  0 + 10\n\nOnce they know these combinations automatically, they begin to see the pattern everywhere.\n\n“Automatically” means they can glance at any number of objects and immediately know its partner.\n\nKids start to add and subtract in their heads. Multiplication and division come easily. Fractions and decimals make instant sense. Finding missing numbers (algebra) is fun. Graphing becomes obvious. Estimating for quick calculations is a snap.\n\n<strong>They start being able to <em>use</em> math in their lives.</strong>\n\nFor instance, they figure out how many more of something they need to reach a goal,  if they can afford to buy an item they want, how to fairly split a bag of M&amp;Ms with friends, or how to help their parents decide on a tip to give the server at a restaurant.\n\nThis small thing—knowing the number partners that make 10—will give your child a huge leg up in math and, quite possibly, in life.\n\nThis math hack builds confidence, especially when kids \"wow\" people with how they figure out things, without having to write them down or grab a calculator.\n\nTake a few minutes to watch Eli, a second-grader, show you how to play the Names for 10 game, and let your son or daughter try it out:\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"wsite-youtube\" style=\"margin-bottom: 40px; margin-top: 10px;\">\n<div class=\"wsite-youtube-wrapper wsite-youtube-size-auto wsite-youtube-align-center\">\n<div class=\"wsite-youtube-container\"><iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/5vD-USijZ8g?wmode=opaque\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Here’s how to ingrain the names for 10 in your child’s brain and give him a leg up for life:</strong>\n<ol>\n 	<li>Set out a pile of something fun to be counted: nuts, cereal, raisins, buttons, pennies, M&amp;Ms—and have your child count out 10 items.</li>\n 	<li>Separate one item to the right of the group and count the objects in each location. Have your child say out loud: “9 + 1 = 10.”</li>\n 	<li>Continue the previous step with one more item moving to the pile on the right until your child reaches: “0 + 10 = 10.”</li>\n 	<li>Now repeat the process starting with: “10 + 0 = 10,” and continue having your child slide one object to the left this time, vocalizing the name for 10: 9 + 1 = 10, 8 + 2 = 10, 7 + 3 = 10 . . . 0 + 10 = 10. This will tactilely and visually illustrate the commutative property of equality (a + b = b + a).</li>\n</ol>\n<em>Note:</em> If your child seems finished with the game and wants to eat the Cheerios, then you’re done for the day. Make sure the next time you play to repeat the first four steps before continuing with the next activity. On the other hand, if your child wants to keep going, have fun!\n<ul>\n 	<li>Grab a clear cup so your child can see the objects inside. Have him repeat steps two through four, placing the cup upside down over the pile the items move to. Challenge your child to say the names for 10 aloud and see if he can say the “number partners” without looking inside the cup. But let him peek if he needs to. Eventually, he’ll know them—when those neural pathways in his brain are solidly connected and the values are firmly implanted in the hypothalamus.</li>\n 	<li>When you think your child is ready for a little more challenge, choose a random number of items to cover with the cup and see if he can “guess” the number of objects by counting the items outside of the cup.</li>\n</ul>\n<em>Note:</em> In the event of a wrong guess, have him count the objects in the pile, then through the clear cup, and say the entire name for 10: “6 + 4 = 10.”\n\nThe Names for 10 game can end here and pick up on another day unless your child is on a roll and wants to keep playing. Then replace the clear cup with a translucent one, and then an opaque one (see video). Challenge your child to tell you how many objects are hidden under the cup given the number of items in the exposed pile, and pick up the cup for him to confirm or amend his answers.\n\nBut be conscious about when your child is getting tired and stop there. You can always pick up the game and do next steps at another time. The most important thing is to have a good time!\n\n<strong>Let us know how the Names for 10 game goes in your house.</strong>\n\nDo you have a good idea for a convenient time and place for kids and parents to play this game? What items did you use to count? Did your son or daughter pick up the number partners that make 10 right away, or do you think you’ll need to play the game some more to get those combinations fully fixed in your child’s brain?\n\n<strong>Please share with us. Other parents and kids will benefit from your ideas and experience!</strong>\n\n</div>\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">\n<div style=\"height: 0px; overflow: hidden;\"></div>\n<a class=\"wsite-button wsite-button-small wsite-button-normal\" href=\"/blog/more-ways-to-play-the-names-for-10-game-to-help-kids-become-math-wizards-and-you-too\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span class=\"wsite-button-inner\">CHECK OUT THE NEXT POST: MORE \"NAMES FOR 10\" GAMES</span></a>\n<div style=\"height: 30px; overflow: hidden;\"></div>\n</div>\n<div>\n<div id=\"659574040749587807\" class=\"wcustomhtml\" style=\"width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;\" align=\"left\"><!-- AddToAny BEGIN -->\n<div class=\"a2a_kit a2a_kit_size_32 a2a_default_style\"></div>\n<script async=\"\" src=\"https://static.addtoany.com/menu/page.js\"><br />\n</script> <!-- AddToAny END -->\n\n</div>\n</div>', 'Names for 10: The Game that Boosts Kids’ Math Skills', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '11-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:49:05', '2018-10-10 19:49:05', '', 11, 'http://localhost:8888/2018/10/10/11-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(91, 1, '2018-10-10 19:49:45', '2018-10-10 19:49:45', '<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none\" style=\"padding-top:0px;padding-bottom:20px;margin-left:0px;margin-right:10px;text-align:center\">\n<a><img src=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/two-boys-3396713-1920_orig.jpg\" alt=\"Brain Stages summer reading\" style=\"width:auto;max-width:100%\"></a>\n<div style=\"display:block;font-size:90%\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align:left;\">\nSummer vacation gives kids lots of opportunities for free play, which is great for mental processing and creativity. The break between grade levels is a perfect time for kids to get lots of exercise, take a breather from academics, and beef up imaginative play.\n\n<strong>That’s why summer reading is so great!</strong>\n\nBooks offer lots of springboard material to spark kids\' imaginations. Besides, going on mental adventures is a great way to pass the time during those lulls that happen on summer days or for winding down at the end of the bedtime ritual before lights out.\n\n<strong>The best part is children who read fun stories and play some of the Brain Stages games won\'t have to struggle to relearn stuff they\'ve forgotten over the break. In fact, their skills will be even sharper for the coming year.</strong>\n\nThe old saying \"practice makes perfect\" may be an overstatement, but most of us have found that we get better at things when we do them often. The scientific reason is repetition refines neural pathways in the brain and makes them more efficient. Conversely, neglecting those connections makes them rusty, and kids can get frustrated trying to get back into the swing of learning when school starts again.\n\nVisit the local library, book store, or both to find loads of fun for your kids (and you).\nIf your child is happy reading independently, awesome, but don\'t discount the together time in sharing stories, taking turns to read aloud. My kids and I used to check out both kinds of books on every trip to the library — one to read by ourselves and one to share.\n\nMy younger daughter and I read together through her high school years. We loved&nbsp; discussing the characters, talking about the stories, and predicting what might happen next.\n\nI miss those days. A lot. Take the opportunity to read with your kids while you can.<span>&nbsp;</span>\n\n<strong>The trick is to get books your kids will LOVE, that will take them on adventures, make them laugh and fantasize about other places, sticky situations, and learn about problem solving.</strong>\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none\" style=\"padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:20px;margin-left:0px;margin-right:0px;text-align:center\">\n<a><img src=\"http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/children-1822474-1920_orig.jpg\" alt=\"Brain Stages reading list\" style=\"width:auto;max-width:100%\"></a>\n<div style=\"display:block;font-size:90%\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align:left;\">\nFiction is about problem solving, and kids — well, all of us — can pick up a lot of ideas for real life reading imaginary stories. Authors go to great lengths to research settings, history, and customs to make their stories authentic (I know. I write young adult fiction).\n\nKids can learn as much from a novel, or more, than from a history or science book because they get exposed to concepts within the context of a story.\n\n<strong>For the next several weeks, I\'m going to post lists of tried-and-true titles that have a great reputation for enthralling scads of kids.</strong>\n\nSome of these books have been around for a while. Some are fairly new. All are awesome reads.\n\n<strong>Each list will be geared for a certain reading level.</strong>\n\n<strong>\n</strong><strong>Today\'s post is for second grade, give or take. And I listed series because good books are like cookies or chips — if your kids like one by a certain author, they\'ll probably want more.</strong>\n\nIf your children aren\'t up to this level yet, these will be wonderful read-aloud books to share. And if they usually read harder books, these titles can be quick and easy entertainment. After all, summer is a time to read for pleasure.\n\nI’ve included a list for girls and a list for boys since the genders often show different interests at this age. But feel free to expose both lists to your son or daughter. The best books are the ones they choose for themselves, and all of these books are fun.\n\n<strong>Please share these lists with your friends! Let\'s get lots of kids reading!</strong>\n\n<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eight Favorite Series of Second Grade Girls (and Boys Too)</strong>\n<ol>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Ivy+and+Bean+series+by+Annie+Barrows\" target=\"_blank\">Ivy and Bean series by Annie Barrows</a>—two unlikely girls become friends and engage in hilarious antics together.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Mercy+Watson+to+the+Rescue+series+by+Kate+DiCamillo&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AMercy+Watson+to+the+Rescue+series+by+Kate+DiCamillo\" target=\"_blank\">Mercy Watson to the Rescue series by Kate DiCamillo</a>—the Watsons’ pet pig gets into all kinds of ridiculous trouble trying to save the day.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Science+Series+by+April+Chloe+Terrazas&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AScience+Series+by+April+Chloe+Terrazas\" target=\"_blank\">Super Smart Science Series for kids by April Chloe Terrazas</a>—complicated science concepts explained in an intriguing, understandable way for the younger set.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Gooney+Bird+Greene+series+by+Lois+Lowry&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AGooney+Bird+Greene+series+by+Lois+Lowry\" target=\"_blank\">Gooney Bird Greene series by Lois Lowry</a>—second-grade girl tells “true stories” to her classmates that are quite outlandish and fun.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Toys+Go+Out%3A+Being+the+Adventures+of+a+Knowledgeable+Stingray%2C+a+Toughy+Little+Buffalo%2C+and+Someone+Called+Plastic+&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AToys+Go+Out%3A+Being+the+Adventures+of+a+Knowledgeable+Stingray%5Cc+a+Toughy+Little+Buffalo%5Cc+and+Someone+Called+Plastic+\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Toys Go Out: Being the Adventures of a Knowledgeable Stingray, a Toughy Little Buffalo, and Someone Called Plastic</em></a> by Emily Jenkins (trilogy)—little girls’ toys and their zany adventures together.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Junie+B.+Jones+series+by+Barbara+Park&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AJunie+B.+Jones+series+by+Barbara+Park\" target=\"_blank\">Junie B. Jones series by Barbara Park</a>—hilarious, charming character kids love.</li>\n 	<li>Judy Moody series by Megan McDonald—feisty, socially awkward third-grader who usually learns lessons the hard way; great early chapter books with fun illustrations.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Amelia+Bedelia+chapter+book+series+by+Herman+Perish&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AAmelia+Bedelia+chapter+book+series+by+Herman+Perish\" target=\"_blank\">Amelia Bedelia chapter book series by Herman Perish</a> (nephew of Peggy Perish, author of the picture book series)—entertaining stories that misinterpret idioms and homophones.</li>\n</ol>\n<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eight Favorite Series of Second Grade Boys (and Girls Too)</strong>\n<ol>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Touchdown+for+Tommy+by+Matt+Christopher&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ATouchdown+for+Tommy+by+Matt+Christopher\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Touchdown for Tommy</em> by Matt Christopher</a>—author of many books about sporty kids.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Stink+series+by+Megan+McDonald&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AStink+series+by+Megan+McDonald\" target=\"_blank\">Stink series by Megan McDonald</a>—Judy Moody’s younger brother, a second-grade boy, gets into all kinds of fun predicaments with the best of intentions.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Stink-O-Pedia%3A+Super+Stink-y+Stuff+from+A+to+ZZZZ++Megan+McDonald&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AStink-O-Pedia%3A+Super+Stink-y+Stuff+from+A+to+ZZZZ++Megan+McDonald\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Stink-O-Pedia: Super Stink-y Stuff from A to ZZZZ</em></a> &nbsp;also by Megan McDonald—a book of gross facts little boys love.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Super+Super+Smart+Science+Series+by+April+Chloe+Terrazas&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ASuper+Super+Smart+Science+Series+by+April+Chloe+Terrazas\" target=\"_blank\">Super Smart Science series for kids by April Chloe Terrazas</a>—complicated science concepts explained in a way kids can understand and feel smart.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Nate+the+Great+series+by+Marjorie+Weinman+Sharmat&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ANate+the+Great+series+by+Marjorie+Weinman+Sharmat\" target=\"_blank\">Nate the Great mystery series by Marjorie Weinman Sharmat</a>—for kids who need practice to get to grade-level reading and like a good whodunit.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Dog+Man+series+by+Dave+Pilkey&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ADog+Man+series+by+Dave+Pilkey\" target=\"_blank\">Dog Man series by Dave Pilkey</a>—his latest silly series that has kids clamoring for more.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Magic+Tree+House+series+by+Mary+Pope+Osborne&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AMagic+Tree+House+series+by+Mary+Pope+Osborne\" target=\"_blank\">Magic Tree House series by Mary Pope Osborne</a>—for various reading levels; brings history to life and promotes conversations about historical events.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Magic+School+Bus+series+by+Joanna+Cole&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AMagic+School+Bus+series+by+Joanna+Cole\" target=\"_blank\">Magic School Bus series—mostly by Joanna Cole</a>, also various reading levels; entertaining read-along books about science concepts learned through adventure.</li>\n</ol>\n<font size=\"4\"><strong>Remember to share this post with your friends. Let\'s get kids reading this summer!</strong></font>\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<div id=\"802094443335514253\" align=\"left\" style=\"width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;\" class=\"wcustomhtml\">\n<!-- AddToAny BEGIN -->\n<div class=\"a2a_kit a2a_kit_size_32 a2a_default_style\">\n<a class=\"a2a_dd\" href=\"https://www.addtoany.com/share\"></a> <a class=\"a2a_button_facebook\"></a> <a class=\"a2a_button_twitter\"></a> <a class=\"a2a_button_google_plus\"></a> <a class=\"a2a_button_linkedin\"></a></div>\n<script async=\"\" src=\"https://static.addtoany.com/menu/page.js\"><br />\n</script> <!-- AddToAny END -->\n\n</div>\n</div>', 'Summer Reading to Keep Kids Sharp: Grade 2', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '13-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:49:45', '2018-10-10 19:49:45', '', 13, 'http://localhost:8888/2018/10/10/13-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
